<subSubSection id="8A398CDFAACC577FAE8A1F7DA3F549AC" pageId="0" pageNumber="81" type="notes">
<paragraph id="165797329E5093D861F219CE520D38FD" pageId="0" pageNumber="81">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="96C65589810AE38B11B420CDA8065F4D" pageId="0" pageNumber="81">
<taxonomicName id="307B605B8FEC5E9F6F7E61A1B81B6D92" class="Sordariomycetes" family="Ceratostomataceae" genus="Microthecium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Microthecium africanum" order="Melanosporales" pageId="0" pageNumber="81" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="africanum">Microthecium africanum</taxonomicName>
is characterized by ostiolate ascomata and punctate, ellipsoidal ascospores. Two asexual morphs with different conidia have been reported: (i), 1
<normalizedToken id="F83714779C6C2D1135446DA9A701B607" originalValue="–4(–">-4(-</normalizedToken>
5)-celled, globose and smooth-walled at first but becoming cylindrical and coarsely verrucose later; (ii), 1-2-celled, large, usually cylindrical and smooth-walled (
<bibRefCitation id="5E488C8A02B6096F29DAF86FA33F842F" author="Krug, JC" journalOrPublisher="Mycologia" pageId="0" pageNumber="81" pagination="414 - 417" title="A new species of Persiciospora from African soil." url="https://doi.org/10.2307/3807643" volume="80" year="1988">Krug 1988</bibRefCitation>
). However, the type strain was probably not a pure culture because the SSU and LSU sequences match with different species of 
<taxonomicName id="CC8BC8D660B5DE894846DCB8AAE9F9AD" class="Sordariomycetes" family="Nectriaceae" genus="Fusarium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Fusarium" order="Hypocreales" pageId="0" pageNumber="81" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">Fusarium</taxonomicName>
and the pictures of the conidia type (i) resemble the chlamydospores produced by several species of this genus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
